pr_title: Refactoring and testing of Interactor classes
pr_body: Refactoring Interactor module to separate Interactor classes from Plotting classes.
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 986769611, 'comment_body': 'I would assume, naively, that the pathpatch need be maintained by the plotting-class. The PathPatch *is* the line, AFAIK.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 10, 4, 11, 50, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'joernu76', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 986829421, 'comment_body': 'OK, had a closer look. This is a mess. There are *two* related objects, the pathpatch (which is not plotted) and the line (which is plotted). Both should be identical and the pathpatch is used to interact with the "path", whereas the line is plotting it.
This might be very useful for your disentanglement, but ultimately, it seems overcomplicated and superfluous.
To get the pathpatch to be plotted, it should be sufficient to set "edgecolor" to "linecolor" (and remove the self.line-plot). This works reasonably well - except for drag-dropping points. The latter could likely be fixed in some fashion, probably, by exchanging the line.set_data-stuff with something similar for the pathpatch.
The whole thing is a tad complicated also due to the distinction between wp_vertices and vertices etc needed by the great-circle paths...', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 10, 4, 12, 54, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'joernu76', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 997900412, 'comment_body': 'The GC stands for "great circle". There are two, separate, path classes (probably for historical reasons; doesn't seem to fill any particular purpose). PathH and PathH_GC, which, presumably deal with horizontal paths in an Euclidian geometry, on the one hand, and on a sphere, on the other.

Please use the GC only for the Horizontal classes. 
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 10, 18, 8, 39, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'joernu76', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 997901103, 'comment_body': 'see above.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 10, 18, 8, 39, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'joernu76', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 997906738, 'comment_body': "I would prefer, for consistency, when you do not supply the wpm model, but only the contained data (similar to redraw_path).
Think about testing! For testing this get_lat_lon function, one needs to create/mock a complicated QT structure, where a simple list of coordinates'd work as well.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 10, 18, 8, 44, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'joernu76', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 997913588, 'comment_body': 'Is it correct that this is removed? I'll change it.
> self.ax.draw_artist(self.pathpatch)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 10, 18, 12, 41, 54, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swsrkty', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1018110724, 'comment_body': "As most of the mslib stuff uses the list of ft.Waypoint's, I would try to remove the need of the waypoints_list1.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 9, 15, 46, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'joernu76', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1018110968, 'comment_body': 'not necessary', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 9, 15, 47, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'joernu76', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1018112841, 'comment_body': 'This should be removed. The "vertices" of the msui classes are often in different units then lon/lat. The restructuring of using update_from_waypoints should have made this superfluous anyway.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 9, 15, 48, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'joernu76', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1018122376, 'comment_body': "The function names do not follow the PEP8 convention. Also adding TopView here seems redundant.

I think it is sensible to have small functions plotting the individual plot components. However calling three functions without any argument in main() seems like a strange design. Why not only one? *In principle* you could put everything in the constructor - or make a simple function doing all that.

What makes sense is reusing the MyFigure class for all plots of one type. But maybe the draw() function should not contain the loop. Instead the loop should IMO go into the main() function and call a draw function with flightpath etc. as  *arguments*.
I also suspect that this does not work properly for multiple flights as, e.g., the label functions must be called after changing the flight.
But maybe I am mistaken, I haven't tested it in practice.
